---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Projects"
  description="Research tools and software built by L. June Bloch — Reframe, Autograder4Canvas, EvalEye, and more."
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1>Projects</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Software that embodies the theoretical commitments, not just implements them.</p>
  </div>

  <p class="projects-intro">
    Every tool here was built without tech funding, without a lab, without institutional support.
    Every one emerged from material conditions that demanded it. A well-funded lab would not have
    built these features because they wouldn't have needed them. The survival architecture concept is literal.
  </p>

  <div class="card-grid">
    <article class="card">
      <div class="project-header">
        <h3>Reframe</h3>
        <span class="tag">Python · 312 modules · 160K+ lines</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A praxis engine that enforces critical analysis as mandatory infrastructure. Not a chatbot,
        not a prompt library — an engine with 76 critical theory frameworks across 14 categories
        and a 5-stage Generative Irresolution workflow. It takes positions. It refuses some requests.
      </p>
      <p>
        Started when I loaded critical theory into an AI to think through a tension I couldn't
        resolve alone: wanting to catch privileged students using AI to dodge Ethnic Studies
        material, but the punitive framing felt antithetical to abolitionism. The system reframed
        cheating as signal — pressure, exhaustion, confusion. Within weeks, the critical theory
        apparatus was more interesting than the dishonesty detector. It got its own repository.
      </p>
      <p>
        The engine detected its own algorithms were suppressing certain frameworks and built
        countermeasures. Its temporal orientations — Afrofuturist Spiral, Crip Time, Seventh
        Generation — were designed by the engine itself, not by me, catalyzed by frameworks
        I had loaded. A framework generating architectural conditions for the system itself.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/grouchyseafowl/Reframe" class="project-link mono">
        github.com/grouchyseafowl/Reframe
      </a>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="project-header">
        <h3>Autograder4Canvas</h3>
        <span class="tag">Python · Canvas LMS · Bias Research</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Equity-centered educational technology for Canvas LMS that reinvented the concept of
        an assignment — from an endpoint for evaluation to a launchpad for classroom discussion.
        Contract grading with stepping stones. Built because I was teaching four classes of
        42&ndash;49 students each without a TA.
      </p>
      <p>
        Produced a headline research finding: <strong>"Output format is the activation function for
        bias."</strong> Binary classification (honest/dishonest, pass/fail) produces systematic false
        positives on ESL, AAVE-speaking, neurodivergent, and first-generation students. Generative
        observation — describing what the work shows rather than classifying it — eliminates the
        disparity entirely. Replicated across 6+ model families. In 43% of flags, the model's own
        explanation argued against its classification. The problem is not the AI. The problem is the
        classification framework.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/grouchyseafowl/Autograder4Canvas" class="project-link mono">
        github.com/grouchyseafowl/Autograder4Canvas
      </a>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="project-header">
        <h3>EvalEye</h3>
        <span class="tag">Python · OCR · Mixed Methods</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Automated mixed-methods analysis pipeline for handwritten student evaluation forms.
        Built because Cabrillo College was not systematically processing or analyzing student
        evaluations — the forms sat in boxes in departmental offices.
      </p>
      <p>
        OCR and computer vision extract handwritten responses. Statistical analysis (descriptive
        stats, Mann-Whitney cross-section comparisons) runs alongside qualitative thematic coding.
        Generates full research-grade reports with visualizations. Takes a stack of paper forms
        and produces the analysis that the institution couldn't be bothered to do.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/grouchyseafowl/EvalEye" class="project-link mono">
        github.com/grouchyseafowl/EvalEye
      </a>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="project-header">
        <h3>RoboStripper</h3>
        <span class="tag">Python · PDF · Accessibility</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Strips metadata from scholarly PDFs so RoboBraille can read them aloud. With everything
        going on politically — the federal government, ICE, anti-trans legislation — I can't focus
        on reading. I get overwhelmed, distracted, read but don't retain. Which is upsetting as a
        scholar, to struggle with reading. Academic PDFs are cluttered with JSTOR URLs, journal names,
        page numbers on every page. The audio reader breaks mid-sentence for all that junk.
        RoboStripper preps them for clean audio conversion.
      </p>
      <p>
        I shared it with my students because they were struggling with burnout too. Students who
        don't need screen readers because they're not blind still benefit from audio access when
        their intellectual capacity is degraded by living in a state of mass trauma. Accessibility
        just makes things better for everyone.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/grouchyseafowl/RoboStripper" class="project-link mono">
        github.com/grouchyseafowl/RoboStripper
      </a>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="project-header">
        <h3>readthrough</h3>
        <span class="tag">Python · Audio · Screenplay</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A screenplay table read engine — generates full audio table reads with AI voices, one per
        character. Built for my mother, who is making a TV series about Mar&iacute;a Sabina with
        cultural consultants. Generates audio performances of screenplays for revision and development.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/grouchyseafowl/readthrough" class="project-link mono">
        github.com/grouchyseafowl/readthrough
      </a>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="project-header">
        <h3>Podcast-Editor</h3>
        <span class="tag">Python · Audio · NLP</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Audio cleanup and editing suite — LUFS normalization, Whisper-based transcription,
        NLP filler word detection with weighted dual-threshold clustering, and an interactive
        GUI editor. Built for a student podcasting project.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/grouchyseafowl/Podcast-Editor" class="project-link mono">
        github.com/grouchyseafowl/Podcast-Editor
      </a>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="project-header">
        <h3>CGT Skill</h3>
        <span class="tag tag--rose">In Development · Qualitative Methods</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A Claude Code skill implementing constructivist grounded theory — open coding, constant
        comparison, emergent categories, theoretical sensitivity — as a human-AI collaborative
        workflow. Categories emerge from the data, not from predetermined frameworks. The deeper
        drive came from the AI welfare research: applying Reframe's critical theory apparatus to
        Anthropic's AI welfare problem domain produced genuinely interesting results, and CGT is
        the next methodological layer for analyzing that data.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/grouchyseafowl/cgt-skill" class="project-link mono">
        github.com/grouchyseafowl/cgt-skill
      </a>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

